Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Library Technician Abbotsford , BC Description Job Summary: UFV invites applications for a two permanent Library Technicians, one 100% FTE and one 50% FTE, to work at the new Mission campus, for an anticipated start date of July 2, 2024. The Library Technician provides front line support and assistance to students, faculty, staff, and the general public, both in person and at a distance. The incumbent undertakes assigned specialized duties that support a wide variety of library services and functions. The Technician opens and closes the library and ensures that the facility and services are functional for library users. The incumbent performs the complete range of library circulation activities using the Integrated Library System (ILS) and the University student records system. The Technician ensures a pleasant and safe learning environment for library users. The Technician: Opens and closes the library, ensuring that the facility and services are fully functional for library users, and that the facility and contents are secured at the end of the day.Performs the complete range of library materials circulation activities using the integrated library system and UFV’s student records system.Applies expertise and leadership to specialized duties in one or more areas including collections support, teaching, and learning support, marketing and public relations support, website and web presence support and assessment support.Calculates, records, and collects fines and fees for various items such as overdue, and lost and damaged materials, issues receipts.Provides individual reference service to assist library users in clarifying and interpreting their information needs.Recommends appropriate materials and sources to meet a user’s needs, by using specialized knowledge of the structure of information resources and knowledge of information tools.Assists library users in the use of library equipment including computers, printers, and photocopiers; maintains and troubleshoots equipment; reports problems.Ensures a pleasant and safe learning environment for library users by monitoring library spaces.Acts for the Manager during regularly scheduled shifts (e.g., evenings, weekends) and in the absence of the Manager, as assigned.Demonstrates and instructs individuals in research techniques and library skills; refers complex research questions to librarians.Contributes to the preparation and revision of procedures documentation; contributes to improving workflows and technical processes.Communicates, implements, and enforces library policies and procedures.Handles confidential records and information ethically.Participates in training and supervising part-time staff, student assistants, and practicum students as required.Responds to security and emergency situations, exercising judgement and following established procedures and guidelines, acts as a floor warden in evacuations.Communicates in a respectful and professional manner with all members of the team, department, University community and external partners.Collaborates effectively as a team member, including sharing information, cross training, and interpersonal cooperation.Demonstrates respect for all members of the UFV community and proactively works to create an environment of inclusivity and accessibility.Actively engages in learning and activities related to actioning indigenization and understanding the impact of colonialism and the purpose of reconciliation.Participates in committees and project teams as required.Undertakes related duties as assigned, consistent with the job grade of the position.Qualifications: Two (2) year Library Technician Diploma from a recognized institution.Two (2) years of related library experience.Proficiency with MS Office programs including Outlook, Word, and Excel.Demonstrated excellent interpersonal and written/oral communication skills.Ability to deal sensitively, effectively, and professionally with students, staff, faculty, and other professional groups as well as the public.Ability to work with a minimum of direct supervision, to establish priorities, achieve deadlines, problem solve, and work well under pressure.Highly resourceful and organized; able to problem solve and self-initiate.Demonstrated attention to detail, ability to deal with changing priorities, frequent interruptions, and diverse personalities.Physical fitness sufficient for moderate physical exertion including pushing, pulling, and lifting library materials up to 40-50 pounds.Banner and FAST experience considered an asset.100% FTE application link: http://clients.njoyn.com/CL3/xweb/xweb.asp?clid=56144&amp;page=jobdetails&amp;jobid=J0524-0588&amp;BRID=EX274070&amp;SBDID=21381&amp;LANG=1 50% FTE application link: http://clients.njoyn.com/CL3/xweb/xweb.asp?clid=56144&amp;page=jobdetails&amp;jobid=J0524-0592&amp;BRID=EX274074&amp;SBDID=21381&amp;LANG=1About UFV:The University of the Fraser Valley is located on the traditional territory of the Halq'eméylem-speaking peoples. We express our gratitude and respect for the honour of living and working in Stó:lō Tém:éxw (Stó:lō Land; Stó:lō World). In all that we do, UFV strives to support and honour the Stó:lō peoples goals of self-determination and well-being on these lands. A commitment to Indigenization and Reconciliation is core to our institutional Vision and Integrated Strategic Plan: IYAQAWTXW — which means House of Transformation. This commitment includes the goal of centering Indigenous ways of knowing throughout our organization, recognizing our responsibilities to community, and a multi-year plan to increase the number of Indigenous faculty, staff, and administrators working at UFV. UFV has four campus locations within the beautiful Fraser Valley in British Columbia. Recognized as one of BC's top employers, UFV offers a combination of career and lifestyle benefits. Join a team of 1,400 passionate professionals who value integrity, inclusivity and excellence. At UFV, you will serve a vibrant community, and shape the future of 15,000 students. Indigenization, equity, and diversity are essential to our work as a university. A diverse community fosters the inclusion of voices that have been historically underrepresented and marginalized. At UFV, we are committed to recruiting a diverse workforce that represents the community we proudly serve. We encourage applications from Indigenous peoples, members of groups that experience discrimination due to race, colour, place of origin, ancestry, and/or religion, persons who identify as women and 2SLGBTQ+, and persons with disabilities. We invite applicants to complete a confidential self-identification survey as part of the application process. All questions are voluntary, with an option to decline to answer. Information will be used to support efforts to broaden the diversity of the recruitment process, and results are not shared with the selection committee. Inquiries about the survey may be directed to careers@ufv.ca. Learn more about our commitment to diversity and inclusion. All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadians and permanent residents will be given priority. In an effort to be both environmentally and fiscally responsible, UFV will contact only candidates receiving an interview. We thank all applicants for considering UFV for employment. Shortlisted applicants may be required to undergo a criminal record check and/ or a verification of their education credentials. UFV is committed to the principle of equity in employment. Compensation 29.40 - 35.43 per hour Closes: 12 June, 2024 University of the Fraser Valley Abbotsford , BC Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
